At the end of the exchanges, the Prague stock exchange plunged into the negative
After the fall of Tuesday morning, the Prague stock exchange rectified its losses.
Transactions with EZ shares reached almost half of the usual daily exchanges.
On Tuesday, from the beginning of the exchanges, the Prague stock exchange resumed with its fall from the previous day, when it lost almost six percent.
This time, the decline is due to the fall in stocks on Wall Street.
The market's reaction to the result of the vote in the U.S. House of Representatives, which refused to adopt the stabilization plan for the U.S. financial sector, is also noticeable here.
Decline in stocks in Asia
Asian stock markets experienced a dramatic fall on Tuesday, even though the indices managed to wipe out some of the losses over the course of the day.
The Hong Kong Stock Exchange’s Hang Seng Index lost four percent during trading, but later wiped out some of the losses and reduced the decline to nearly 2.5 percent.
The Hong Kong Stock Exchange’s Hang Seng China Enterprises Index lost 3.8 percent as markets were closed in Shanghai.
Shares on the Sydney Stock Exchange were losing more than five percent, but eventually the losses were reduced to 4.3 percent.
According to its index, the Taiwan Stock Exchange lost 3.6 percent.
“The hesitation about bailout action in the U.S. will affect financial markets around the world,” said Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Monetary Office.
Although Hong Kong is part of China, it establishes its monetary policy itself, i.e. independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as in the United States.
Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd said U.S. lawmakers should quickly resume negotiations and adopt the proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, other countries may be affected.
The Bloodbath of American Actions
On Monday, the U.S. House of Representatives rejected the plan to support the financial system, to which it should have spent up to $700 billion (nearly $12 trillion).
Legislators thus renounced the call for support for President George Bush's project.
According to Bush, the project should solve the main causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks suffered a bloodbath on Monday and major stock indices saw the biggest drop in the past 20 years.
The Dow Jones index lost nearly seven percent, having experienced a drop of this magnitude for the last time in 1987.
The index was already losing during the vote, but when it appeared that the proposal had not been adopted, it was in free fall.
Congress Gives Up: US Government Can Inject $700 Billion into Banks
The leaders of the U.S. Congress and the government of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of the financial aid agreement for the U.S. financial system.
It will be put to the vote early next week.
U.S. lawmakers made a decisive turning point in talks on the adoption of a bailout plan in the form of $700 billion (about 12 trillion kroner) in financial aid to the U.S. financial system.
Success is not certain.
Indeed, before they can publish the final version of the law and put it to the vote, Congressmen must complete a number of details of the agreement.
The financial system support plan will be discussed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
Barney Frank, chairman of the House Banking and Financial Regulatory Committee, told Reuters on Sunday.
According to sources, the plan should be put to a vote in the Senate on Wednesday at the earliest.
According to economists, the announcement that the bailout will be adopted should be a major psychological first factor in reviving financial markets.
However, given the complexity of the mechanisms by which aid to markets can be effective, a "disillusionment" will follow.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We have made great progress.
We have settled our differing views on how the package of measures for stabilizing the market should be shaped,” Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg News Agency.
The final vote could be taken as early as Sunday.
On the night of Saturday to Sunday, lawmakers met with U.S. Finance Minister Henry Paulson to give the government its final form.
It is expected to repurchase from financial corporations the unsold real estate assets that lead financial firms to considerable losses and threaten the stability of the system as a whole.
“We are about to agree on a plan that will work and must also be effective in the market.
We still need to continue this plan to restore markets, but I think we are here," Paulson said.
A signal for Asian trade
The global financial crisis has a significant impact on falling equity markets.
According to the Democratic senator do not evade Harry Reid, lawmakers make sure that Congress reaches a definitive agreement as early as Sunday.
They want to calm investors ahead of the start of trade in Asian financial markets, which are located in the first time zone, where the congressional decision could affect trade on Monday.
But at the moment, it is impossible to say with certainty when the two Houses of Congress will proceed to the vote, nor if the negotiations are not likely to remain blocked, at the last moment, by this or that problem.
Lawmakers hope it will be adopted in the coming days.
However, the law will still undergo many changes.
The total amount allocated to the system shall be divided into two parts.
The first $350 billion, as President George Bush wanted, should be available as soon as possible.
But if Congress has the impression that the program is not fulfilling its function, it has the possibility of blocking the granting of the remaining amount, following two steps: first an additional 100 billion dollars, then, finally, 350 billion dollars.
Mr. Bush praised progress in negotiations
Although the president may veto this decision, Congress has the option of putting it in the minority.
Despite these changes, the main idea of the program, which consisted of obtaining finances for the purchase of bad real estate securities, the value of which fell, because hundreds of thousands of Americans are not able to pay their mortgages, was maintained.
“All the work is done.
The House of Representatives should be able to pass the bill on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday,” said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
U.S. President George Bush himself is pleased with the progress in the negotiations.
Spokesman Tony Fratto said Bush was pleased with the progress made on Saturday and appreciated "the bipartisan effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy."
Limitation of golden parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, chief negotiator, said lawmakers agreed on the responsibility of the financial program, protecting contributors from losses, agreeing on relief, and moving the plan along the time axis.
The new law also provides for the limitation of gold parachutes for directors of participating companies and establishes a committee to oversee the fund.
The latter should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
“We have worked very hard on the issue and made significant progress towards a deal that will work and be effective for the market and for all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also provides help for homeowners, who have problems paying.
The government should negotiate new advances in the case of mortgages it will buy back, while reducing the monthly payments of debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
According to Patria Finance Chief Economist David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but its implementation will be very difficult.
“And that’s because we don’t know what the mechanism and price will be for repurchasing the troubled assets.
This point will be decisive in deciding on the sharing of losses between the financial sector and the government," Marek told iHNed.cz this week.
Whether the plan will be adopted now, or early next week, is, according to Marek, not that important.
“It’s much more important that congressmen agree this week that they will support this plan and commit to it as soon as possible.
This psychological significance of the agreement, providing for the adoption of the plan, matters most at the moment," Marek said.
A struggle pushed to the extreme: MP3 players against mobiles.
We will advise you, how to choose
While virtually all mobiles know how to play MP3 files, no MP3 player knows how to call.
It seems clear that it is better to buy only a phone.
However, there are enough reasons to get an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the way of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy an expensive high-end gramophone for home to put Maxim Turbulenc's new album.
On the one hand, such musical products do not come out on vinyl record, and, from a quality point of view, there is no objective reason for this to happen.
Now, if there are vinyl records in your shelves piled up, with rock art, jazz or blues, you are at least probably dreaming of such a gramophone.
The same goes for music on the go, i.e. compressed music, so to speak in a simplified way - music in MP3.
There are also categories based on price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns for a player, just as a Pink Floyd fan would struggle to support headphones purchased for twenty crowns at the market.
These are two extremes, between which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
Battery life is also crucial
Some high-end music players are capable of much more than just playing music, but these are unknown features, of course, from most mobiles.
No current device is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the primary functions, phone calls and sending SMS, it is able to play music and movies, record them, it has a camera of varying quality and can, for example, even serve for navigation.
And if you take smartphones and communicators into account, you’ll have a small computer in your pocket.
Since no refrigerator knows how to grill meat and no television will take photographs, we are virtually witnessing a miracle.
However, the universal character of the mobile is not without drawbacks.
The larger the number of functions you use, the shorter the interval between reloads.
And playing music is one of the most important energy waves.
There are few mobile phones that are able to play music for ten to twelve hours, in most cases, this figure is much lower.
In this regard, music players (especially the most rudimentary) are much better performers.
In the case of cheap mobile phones, expect that they will only play music for a few hours.
If, in addition, you happen to call from time to time, get, to be sure, a second charge for the job - this is valid even for more expensive devices.
The problem will not arise for MP3 players, which are capable, following a reload, of continuous operation of at least 9 hours, including the less efficient ones.
Another problem occurs when recording music in mobile.
Unfortunately, a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector, especially since not all of them can be directly connected to the computer, without special software.
It is obviously possible to record music directly on the memory card, but few card readers know how to do it without reduction, given the tiny dimensions of the memory cards used in the mobiles.
As for the drives, you do not need, except for the iPod, any software.
Simply fill in, through the USB connector, the music device coming from the computer.
Most mobiles and players will create a media library themselves, sorted by the performer's name, album title, style, or user's judgment.
Some devices only display an index with a tree structure, like the Windows Explorer, others are capable of both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Readers are easier to manipulate, mobiles have more know-how
When choosing a specific device, be especially interested in the battery life, memory capacity, quality and type of sound output and, of course, ease of control.
If the music is for you, essentially, a background sound and if in the day you are going to listen to it only for a limited time, for example by taking the tram, you just have any mobile playing MP3.
Virtually every mobile device is capable of doing this today.
You don’t even have to pay too much attention to the music formats that the mobile or player is able to play.
They all manage to play MP3s and the vast majority of the music that will reach you will have just that format.
It is one of the most popular formats and apart from it, the vast majority of devices can also play WMA-format music.
The AAC (format used by Apple and its iPods) is less common.
High-end mobiles also allow, for example, the purchase of music online.
Just visit, from the mobile phone, the corresponding web pages of the operator (or those of another provider) and buy the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a compelling reason to purchase a musical device.
The offer of operators is unfortunately miserable and it is limited, in most cases, to quickly made radio tubes.
Prices are not the lowest either.
Nevertheless, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (whether by GSM, internet, or even wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their mobile on themselves.
Whenever you feel like listening to something, you just need to get the phone out of your pocket, when you’ve forgotten your MP3 player at home.
However, it is also important if you always have headphones or a handsfree with connection.
If not, you can use the built-in speakers, which have virtually all mobiles, but a minimum of MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of mobile music is its price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand.
For a price of three or four thousand crowns, you can have a Walkman already very suitable.
However, in most cases, you will be limited by the absence of output for regular headphones.
The price of the best phones and the best tools, also equipped with an input for ordinary headphones, does not exceed fifteen thousand.
Readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of having an easy command.
Truly anyone manages to ensure the command of the most rudimentary readers - who do not necessarily correspond to the cheapest ones (cf. our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the resemblance of the control to that of a cassette station, commonly used in the past, or a gramophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of a collision in the form of a randomly connected mobile internet, followed by a huge data transmission invoice.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. the Vodafone 527) usually have an exchangeable memory card slot (the M2, microSD, and so on).
Even taking into account the additional purchase of such a card, you are not going to exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
Basic models only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive ones get away with even 8GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile phone and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, an Emgeton, or an iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you should not spend more than 1,100 kronor.
If you are one of the most demanding listeners, choose specialized walkman mobiles (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices are provided with independent control keys for MP3, and this is how the ease of control approximates that of an independent MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose mobiles in the walkman series have the same user menu as MP3 players sold separately, is the one that has gone the most in this field.
The same service, in the same price category, but with a memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and a longer battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours) is provided by an MP3 player produced by one of the brands mentioned above.
A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced, with our operators offering virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force conventional operators to lower prices.
It may not be missing for a long time.
We have already mentioned on Mobil.cz that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The Czech Telecommunication Office, which reported that the price of an SMS was higher in our country than in the rest of the Union, confirmed this.
Thus, following the latest steps by the European Commission in the regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation may occur - text messages sent from abroad will be for some customers of Czech mobile operators cheaper than in the country.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really like to enter the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and penetration that far exceeds 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this regard, Pavel Dvosak, the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunication Office (CTO), who has repeatedly stated that in the Czech Republic there is no room for another operator, choruses with the operators.
It is probably true that a conventional operator with its own network is apparently not very lucky (by the way, now it would find only difficult frequencies).
However, there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that has led to a considerable drop in prices, to which conventional operators must subsequently also react.
Yet, even before holiday troublemakers such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the market, voices similar to those we hear today were heard in Britain.
However, it turned out that there was room for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We do not have to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you about the launch in Poland of the virtual operator Mobilking.
In just six months, this operator has managed to win more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth operator in the country.
It should be added that behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns the U:fon in Czechia, among others.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete target group.
For their operation to be effective, they need far fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They are, in fact, exempt from the relatively high costs of construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
This is how virtual operators around the world profile themselves as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often counterbalanced by a limited service offering.
Tesco Mobile, for example, offers SMS at least twice as much as its competitors in the UK.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on an unusual target group can also be a good publicity shot.
Indeed, this operator specifically targets men.
“Real men choose Mobilking – an operator they like and can trust,” said David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It’s hard to say, if such a concept would be likely to work at home as well.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav ?epick? said: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Especially since it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the supply of services."
In the Czech Republic, no chance, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
“We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations are not very supportive.
Instead, the launch of Mobilking will take place in other countries in our area,” Jana Studniková, a spokesman for the Penta financial group, said in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
It thus indirectly confirmed that the operators in the Czech Republic were, in any event, not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything possible so that a potential competitor cannot appear.
The GTS Novera group, which would like to take a new step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefonika in the field of corporate customers, has not been hiding, for quite some time, its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
“We want to be able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have already negotiated this possibility several times with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have managed to move forward in the negotiations," said group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
Perhaps the future is promising.
According to unofficial information, it looks like we might be able to host the first virtual operator by the end of the year.
But for now, his creation is accompanied by total silence.
“Right now, we don’t think there’s room in the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is in comparison with others very specific.
At the moment, no topic with a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us," said Vlastimil Srääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääääää
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová said in a rare agreement with O2's statement: "We have not yet recorded a viable and bilaterally advantageous project, which could serve as a base."
She added: “It is virtually excluded that a virtual operator will appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
To operate in such a limited timeframe, we should have a concrete agreement now.”
Vodafone instead directs its attention to fulfilling the requests to obtain its own 3G license.
Miroslav Sepick said: “We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of shared fees and infrastructures.
This is what we believe means the most input from the customer’s point of view.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to set up a common network for fast mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities: in tune with operators
The approach of mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a decrease in prices and therefore to a decrease in their profit.
What’s the point of making it easier for such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, operators know how to understand themselves as fair thieves. The chicane accompanying the creation of the U:fon also testifies to this.
The biggest apparent pressure on the T, when the U:fon was created, was that exerted by the company T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the T’s web pages.
Today, U:fon serves as an argument for not accepting a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted in this regard: “Competition in the mobile market has also recently been amplified by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the character of the mobile market in RT, it is obvious that the entry of an additional player would subject him, and especially his services, to high demands."
But given the attitude of the mobile operators here, the indifference of the Czech regulators seems bewildering.
However, it is not only about the attitude of the T, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
The latter belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (OHS).
However, the latter adopted, in the face of this problem, its typical position.
The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator in question regarding the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been reached at the moment, as the offer of potential stakeholders has a priori not been of sufficient interest to conventional operators," Kristián Chalupa, from the OHS Department of External Relations, said in a statement.
Such a declaration would not surprise representatives of the operators.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and among other things also take care, that no one takes advantage of its position in the market, such a declaration is more than confusing.
Kristián Chalupa adds: "Overseas, where virtual operators are normally present, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile phone services."
However, pushing for fair market functioning and price reductions is apparently not in the interests of the OHS.
What is indeed shocking is the almost touching agreement of the three mobile operators, which stems from their reactions.
The question, if this is really a coincidence, naturally arises.
In the same way, a price of gasoline that is strictly identical to all gas stations is probably due to chance and the hard fight of the competition.
"The Office has not found, in this regard, signs of anti-competitive behaviour, so it has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, and therefore none has an increased corresponding responsibility for its behaviour on the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile market to virtual operators are probably lacking even at the telecommunications regulator,” Chaloupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many points of contention.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by the ‘T’, according to which telecommunications constitute, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators has a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts propose a different view of things: in order for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, it is necessary to obtain, each time, the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator has quite logically a monopoly on its network.
This is how he necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of his activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for the OHS that three mobile operators visibly proceed in a similar manner.
However, the complaints of many interested parties (including the company GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Getting the responsibility back on the T is a fairly common turn in communications, through which the OHS washes its hands of the case.
We have already encountered this type of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recently adopted telecommunications law has failed to bring about an expansion of the OT's powers in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many experts have promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the OHS must know this very well, but their interests seem to lie elsewhere.
When no one is watching, it can work.
That said, the functioning of some sort of pseudo-virtual operators, several in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that publish their own price lists of mobile phone services, but these are only partially public.
In most cases, it is about companies dealing with multi-level marketing.
Personalized mobile phone services are offered by, for example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms usually only reach elected officials.
The magic trick consists in the fact that the company does in front of the operator figure of a classic business customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, she gets special pricing (and other) offers.
What is problematic is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a resale.
"If what you're talking about happens, it could be a breach of the contractual terms that we would consider and that could result in a stoppage of collaboration with the company in question," Martina Kemrová said.
However, it is quite unlikely that an echo of such activity has reached the heads of mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned it can be thousands of customers.
However, no operator has spoken out against such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these companies bring them significant benefits, and, at the same time, as opposed to real virtual operators, they do not threaten them in any way with their own official marketing.
Miroslav ?epick? points out the possible problems: "The law allows such speculations, however, the services of these companies are only used by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it, in the manner of ordinary customers of mobile operators."
But that is precisely what should seem strange to you.
There is also another question in the OHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such a procedure, why do they block the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the OHS has relatively broad powers to disclose such an activity, and if it does not wish to be satisfied with the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions prohibit it.
When we are no longer the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned on several occasions, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a considerable decrease in the price of services.
However, in virtually all countries where virtual operators appeared, conventional operators sometimes tried more, sometimes less, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were practically the same - a market too small, if not too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In developed countries, however, it was precisely at this level that regulatory bodies intervened, defending not the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Both through formal measurements and informal pressure, they eventually obtained the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, Czech regulators treat this issue like a hot potato that is discarded by passing it on to a nearby target.
As a result of the experiences we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that confusion in their skills is in these cases more than beneficial.
But let's not throw the stick after the bang.
If the behind-the-scenes information is true and a virtual operator will soon appear at us, the Czech mobile market may be back in motion.
If one of the operators has agreed to the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult for the OHS to remain impassive in the face of rejection (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And we may stop calling it more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
