Sudetenland demanded a referendum in the US
In 1945, the Sudeten Germans demanded that Umava be integrated into the United States.
This stems from a letter deposited in the collections of the Jihoeská vädecká knihovna (The Scientific Library of Southern Bohemia).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to at least live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, some groups of Sudeten Germans allegedly addressed the President of the United States with such a desire.
This stems, among other things, from a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of the Jihoeská vädecká knihovna.
In the letter, the Germans from Krumlov asked the US president not to allow "Sumavská ?upa" (forest region south of Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
“We understand the situation and we want to be really sure that the words proclaim that American troops come to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators,” the letter read.
Given that rallying to Czechoslovakia is purportedly promising - knowing the Czech national character - only brutality, inconsiderate attitude, misunderstanding, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter urge the American president to take into his hands the protectorate of the Umava for now and forever.
“We cannot believe that you would grant this territory to a state foreign to us, which oppresses and destroys minorities and has contributed nothing to the victory of the Allies without taking into account the opinion of a quarter of a million people,” the letter reads.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire for revenge of the "Czech oppressors".
If the president of the United States doubted the opinion of the Germans of ?umava, he would only have to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to establish whether its inhabitants wanted to be part of the United States, or to live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text contained in the letter may, in view of current knowledge of postwar history, seem somewhat naïve, according to some survivors, it illustrates well the expectations of the Sudeten Germans of the time.
While the Czech Germans had to at least foresee that the question of their expulsion from the republic would arise, very few of them admitted such a possibility.
Some expected that the United States and Britain would obtain a certain type of autonomy for the Sudetenland.
Others believed that they would simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, who was born in the town of ?eské Bud?jovice, confirms this.
During the war, he was, as a German to Cheské Budajovice, engaged in the navy in the Baltic countries.
When at the end of the war he was captured by the English and placed in the capture camp of the Holstein region, dozens of Czech Germans came to consult him to teach them Czech.
“They believed that once they returned home, the Czech would be of benefit to them,” Chalupa said.
None of the captured Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war believed he would be expelled from the republic as a result of the Benesh Decrees.
You don't think - you pay!
An emotional campaign will attack drivers
The most expensive road safety action in Czech history.
A way to characterize the emotional media campaign that intends to launch, Wednesday, the Ministry of Transport.
The Office of Minister Alești Ebișek believes that it will discourage drivers from dangerous driving behavior.
This $150 million campaign will appear on television, radio, cinema, the internet, but also on flyers.
It should discourage drivers from fast driving and alcohol behind the wheel.
But also remind them to take the belt before starting.
Above all, it wants to touch the conscience of young drivers, bikers, pedestrians, not to mention professional drivers.
What will appear in the spots?
Especially personal stories that will attack emotions.
This is also reflected in the campaign’s “bloody” slogan:
You don't think - you pay!
The phrase "You don't think" is capitalized on the license plate.
Then, in a pool of blood, there's the phrase "You'll pay."
Which must symbolize that one can pay with one’s life a moment of inattention.
The spots will “have” spectators until 2010.
The ministry was inspired by similar campaigns in Anglo-Saxon countries, where images with drastic images of the victims of the accidents are commonly seen.
It believes that this will lead to a decrease in the accident rate and the number of deaths on Czech roads.
The spots were prepared by the Euro RSCG agency.
The sugar and whip strategy against drivers
“What works with drivers is the sugar and whip system.
For them, sugar is represented, for example, by saving time, when they grill a red light.
The whip is the threat of a fine or an accident.
The risks must be reminded to drivers," said Martin Kozán, a transport psychologist at Na Homolce Hospital.
This is how we need information campaigns in the press and especially negative advertisements, the psychologist believes.
Signs signaling danger to drivers are already less effective.
"When a static panel that warns against a danger is installed, it will probably quickly merge with the environment and drivers will not notice it anymore," Kozán said.
