Insomnia Nights for Hypo Real Estate Shareholders
The German banking system is relatively stable, the Federal Minister of Finance insisted only a few weeks ago.
What a good chance that the politician used the word ‘relatively’ and slipped that the German banking sector would not be spared by the crisis movements.
This one actually happened this weekend.
The Bavarian real estate financier Hypo Real Estate (HRE), on the side of the DAX, obtains from a consortium of German banks a loan of one billion to protect itself from market turbulence.
A person familiar with the situation told Reuters on Monday that the aid credits are being issued up to a sum of 35 billion euros.
The Hypo Real Estate would now have to pay interest on the fraction to which it would be entitled.
The money comes as much from private banks as from public-law banks.
In the background, it is daughter company Depfa who bears the losses.
The state financier had, according to a newspaper article, refinanced himself in the very short term for long-term projects for which he had borrowed money – which is no longer possible because of his distrust of the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the bank's liquidity reserve had been reduced by 95 percent to 2.37 million euros, while the equity rate had also slightly decreased from 1.6 percent to 1.45 percent.
Ongoing and net earnings from financial transactions had fallen to zero compared to the same period the previous year, earnings from the allocation of defined receivables and securities as well as the termination of provisions in credit operations had fallen by more than 70 percent to 5 million euros.
And it was only thanks to the significant profits derived from the reimbursement of downstream accounting costs arising from the restructuring of the former Depfa group, as well as the reimbursement of interest according to the book of tax procedures and commercial purchases for the companies of Konzern that the profit deficit of about 16 percent turned out to be moderate.
After his privatization in 1990, the former state financier had initially badly speculated on industrial real estate loans, which had then been branched out to the Aareal bank.
Because conventional state funding was not profitable enough, Depfa had then engaged more intensively in infrastructure projects and in the financing of projects between private investors and the state (PPP) and internationally diversified.
On the value of the daughter company, the Hypo Real Estate must make amortizations that should have an essential material effect on the calculation of the group’s earnings and losses, which is still quite unclear.
The fact is that the dividends have been amputated.
By 2007, they had been cut to two-thirds.
Since the acquisition of Depfa, Hypo Real Estate has been a highly important state and infrastructure investor.
It is stronger than other refinancing-dependent institutions in the inter-bank market since it has no client repositories.
With the bankruptcy of investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, the allocation of credit between banks has once again drastically stopped, as banks have accumulated their liquidity.
The Hypo Real Estate needs a portion – about 50 billion euros – of Depfa’s total loans annually as a short-term means of refinancing.
According to a statement from Hypo Real Estate, the group’s financing need is covered with medium-term credit and the company protected from the influence of international financial markets that are currently largely out of order.
Other sources say the refinancing would be ensured through the funds until the end of 2009.
HRE Chairman Georg Funke said the Hypo Real Estate group should no longer have to resort to medium-term financial markets.
The Federal Bank and the Federal Financial Services Surveillance Institution (Bafin) assume that the Hypo Real Group's market capacity is now assured.
The bank’s shareholders and creditors have only to hope for.
However, given the dynamics and imponderability of the crisis, there is no certainty.
Moreover, it is not unthinkable that funding should not be used in its entirety.
Nor can the opposite be ruled out.
After the bank is, according to the latest press releases, still on the doorstep of insolvency late Sunday evening, this rescue at least provisional will not succeed in reassuring minds either.
The stock price collapsed from 75 percent to 3.30 euros.
Bond prices, on the other hand, are doing particularly well.
While debts in the first place have barely moved, the prices of second-tier loans are declining.
The most affected are the investment funds of the former daughter company Württemberg Hypo and of course those that have a lifespan beyond 2009.
The bonds of Hypo Real Estate seemed to be an alternative speculation investment, now their value must be considered dependent on the stability of the international banking system after the net hardening of the banking crisis and the crisis of the very institute that brought the crisis into the institution by the purchase of Depfa Bank.
As long as less-affected issuing institutions, governments and commercial banks are still ready to support the system, one can assume that arrears will be resolved over time.
Or what no one dares to hope right now will happen – that the financial crisis can be overcome in the next 15 months.
But in the face of the renewed sounds of partial nationalization, the probability that approached certainty has now become a mere well-founded hope.
This should set aside sleepless nights primarily for long-term creditors on the decision whether to separate from their commitments.
Short-term investors can still use what they have drawn a line on to constitute a deferral of losses for the next few years to the next automatically levied capital gains tax.
