Rats also have sensations.
A rat or a cockroach runs away from danger, does that mean they also feel fear?
Neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced of this: many animals also have sensations.
But how could we verify that he feels the same when he behaves the same way we do?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to have proof of it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove it until now just as we cannot prove that other human beings have a consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and address the issues of feeling or consciousness in general, we enter hard-to-reach terrain because the hardware doesn’t match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it kills, flees or attacks.
Human beings behave the same way, which is why some scientists deduce a comparable subjective experience.
However, I do not believe it.
Two aspects of the structure of the brain make transposing our subjective experience to that of animals difficult.
One aspect is that the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the prefrontal lateral cortex (because of its participation in short-term memory and in the functions of direction and execution).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and appears to be entirely absent in other beings.
So at least for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, among which the awareness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that the human being is even different from other primates.
Another significant peculiarity could lie in the linguistic nature of man: much of his existence being related to language, this often means that his consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness were not to depend on language, it would surely influence it, so that animal consciousness, no matter how it is produced, would probably differ a lot from most of our states of consciousness.
This is why it is also difficult to determine what consciousness can look like in other animals.
If this, both internal and subjective, is not measured or, because of this particular Hardware, analyzed based on our own experience, then its observation poses great problems for us.
Most of my developments refer to the content of conscious experience, but there is next to another aspect of consciousness that should be more easily accessible scientifically.
Animal consciousness processes could be examined without regard to their content, and this is exactly what has happened in studies on the short-term memory of primates, particularly with the example of visualization.
But in this approach that Christof Koch and Francis Crick followed, we focus more on the nerve correlations of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: both may or may not be identical.
Curiously, this approach also highlights the weight of the prefrontal cortex in the realization of visualization.
But what happens to the emotions?
I conclude that an emotional system such as that of fear is activated in a brain conscious of its own activity.
