"I photograph the master off-stage to capture elements of his character" Günther Bauer - Photographer
No heels, no stitching clothes.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, freed from all tensions to obtain the relaxed appearance of man or woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other hand, the person.
Inseparable except in intimacy, in those moments unknown to the general public, where we discover to intimate gestures and stolen looks of artists who do not care to go on stage.
The German Günther Bauer mixes in "Flamenco - people" the theatricality of some stagings with singers, dancers and guitarists with this side less known to artists.
In this project, the photographer takes the particular iconography of flamenco from different angles.
Included in the Flemish Photography Month program, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, which is growing every day," explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco - people" "can be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that they are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people photographed “in the street” are artists capable of conveying on stage passion, sadness, joy ... by captivating the audience.
To capture moments of personality of these artists you do not have to take pictures on stage.
They have a personality and a character of their own.
What interested me was to create an intimate atmosphere that allowed me to capture with the camera the personality moments of the flamenco stars.”
With the "Song of Mines" festival, Bauer began in 1997 a long journey to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a plate camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and equipment, recall classic photography.
The implementation of different stylistic means breaks with the classical side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of flamenco according to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and surprises every day".
It is not about the dance or the song itself, but about the personality and character of the artist who captivates the audience with his art.
The search for the essentials and magic has been the constant of this work that is presented these days at the El Fotómata gallery.
The flamenco stars like Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from about seventy photographed artists.
The project has transformed into an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a collection book of the portraits exhibited at the gallery.
Bauer's passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits of Old Athletes" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people", the photographer admits that he loves photographing people's portraits, getting to know them and being able to enter their lives for a more or less long moment.
I believe that in photography portraiture is the most difficult genre.
You find yourself in front of people, characters that sometimes you don’t know or that leave you only a few minutes to be able to take a photo of them.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true.”
This collection of portraits of the current flamenco, called "Flamenco - people", is on display at Galerie El Fotómata, located at number 20 in rue de la Mata (street parallel to the Herculean People's Market), which will be open until 16 October.
