Talking to Sleep
Some kids talk at night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very awake telling us something that happened the day before, but to children who talk while they sleep.
The first time this happens it may surprise you, but in reality it doesn’t matter.
This is a mild sleep disorder called somniloquie.
This is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
Of course, there are more than one person who speaks at night.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (once in life for example associated with an episode of high fever), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the child remembers nothing.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance.
They are often linked to other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night terrors, nocturnal bedwetting, or sleepwalking, but this is not always the case.
As we have said before, they can also be associated with very high fevers, stress or overexcitement.
Either way, this is a little studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it occurs is also very variable.
He may speak in a quiet little voice, with isolated words, whispers or, on the contrary, with screams, tears, long speeches...
In the event that sleepiness becomes very common, it would be wise to observe the child and consult a specialist, to check if there is a problem that causes a lot of anxiety and in order to get an explanation for this problem.
We said this is a benign alteration, which is why there is no treatment, unless it is related to another sleep alteration that can be treated (for example, if it is related to sleep apnea or stress).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child before going to sleep.
So look for quiet games and avoid programs or TV shows that are more or less violent.
With children who are very nervous and have trouble relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them calm down internally.
This will allow the child to have a more peaceful sleep.
As soon as the sleeping pills appear, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember what happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him up.
