Sarkozy meets Angry Fishermen
Before flying to the United States, Nicolas Sarkozy will make a detour through Brittany.
Faced with the demonstration of strength of the fishermen who severely disturbed the accesses to several Breton and Norman ports on Monday, the President of the Republic decided to go Tuesday morning to the port of Guilvinec, in the Finistère, to meet their representatives.
They have promised to welcome him "in a constructive spirit" and hope that he "will come with concrete proposals".
A presidential visit that falls at the same time as a general assembly of the "crisis committee" created by the Breton fishermen to get measures in the face of the surge in gas oil prices, which reached a record of more than 1.14 euros per liter on average.
According to the spokesman of the Elysée David Martinon, the president "will discuss with them solutions that can be imagined to help their companies regain competitiveness and to secure the conditions of employment and remuneration of sailors".
Nicolas Sarkozy is expected to stand firm by the fishermen.
On Tuesday morning, they conducted snail operations in Morbihan and Calvados, causing closures of nearly 10 km.
The marina of Quiberon was also blocked, but the connections to Belle-île did not stop.
A filtering dam has been put in place on the Quiberon peninsula.
The sailors have already shown their determination Monday by burning, from dawn, tires and pallets in front of the fuel depots of the ports of Brest, and Lorient, while demonstrations were taking place in Concarneau or Saint-Brieuc.
The movement spread to other ports on the Atlantic and Channel fronts, such as Les Sables d'Olonne, in the Vendée, where trawlers remained at the dock, or in Le Havre, where some twenty boats blocked the movements of commercial vessels.
The fishermen of La Turballe and Croisic, in the Loire-Atlantique, stopped in the evening the blockade of the important Total refinery of Donges.
Those of Boulogne-sur-Mer decided to wait for Wednesday's meeting at the ministry to decide on possible actions.
In Guilvinec, the "crisis committee" must decide Tuesday on the follow-up to the movement and its participation in the interview scheduled for the Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries in Paris.
But some Breton fishermen do not want to be represented by officials of the National Fisheries Committee, which has not supported their movement.
"The strike will continue" because "the fishermen will not let go of anything" and "do not want to move to Paris", for example announced Liliane Cariou, the president of the Lorient Fisheries Committee.
Professional fishermen, who do not pay taxes on diesel, currently pay about 50 cents per liter but they believe that the threshold of profitability of a boat is reached only with a diesel of less than 0.30 euros per liter.
