Already depressed at the beginning of the session, Wall Street sank after the unexpected rejection by the House of Representatives of the bank bailout plan that was supposed to restore some stability in the markets.
By 228 votes against and 205 votes in favour, representatives denied Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson the means he requested.
Nearly two in three Republicans rejected his plan.
“It’s a bad signal to the market that Congress is unable to adopt a plan,” said Lindsey Piegza of FTN Financial.
“It shows how much the market relied on this plan,” she added, fearing that a project adopted in several days would come “too late.”
“If the project is actually moribund...then the relay will be quickly passed to the Fed and other central banks to manage the crisis, which would further tighten credit conditions,” Brian Bethune, chief economist at Global Insight, said in a statement.
“Every day that passes brings the downfall of a financial institution in the United States,” said Piegza.
After the bankruptcy of Washington Mutual on Friday, the authorities arranged for his rival Citigroup to buy Wachovia’s banking activities.
In Europe, the crisis has accelerated sharply, prompting emergency interventions for banks in the UK, Benelux, Iceland and Germany, signaling that markets are facing “not just a US crisis, but a global crisis,” the FTN Financial analyst added.
The bond market has risen sharply.
The 10-year Treasury yield fell to 3.632 percent, down from 3.827 percent on Friday night, and the 30-year-old to 4.161 percent, down from 4.357 percent the day before.
