In Minsk, "did you notice that there was an election?"
Young people and opponents were demonstrating on Sunday night in the main square of the Belarusian capital to reject the results of the legislative elections in advance.
A few hundred Belarusians gathered Sunday evening as soon as the polling stations in the central square of Minsk closed to protest against the fraudulent nature of the legislatures.
While no results had yet been announced, many young people had come to protest against the power of President Alexander Lukashenko: "the dictator, resign".
Some admit they didn’t even vote: “What good, since they’ll do what they want with my voice,” one young man says.
They do not believe that the regime that has made good use of foreign observers with the aim of resuming its language with the European Union is ready to make a democratic turn.
The sanctions, including a visa ban for 40 Belarusian leaders and the freezing of certain assets, could be lifted if the elections were considered clean by observers.
They were not according to the opposition.
"We have been kept away from electoral commissions and our observers have not been able to participate in the counting," said Yuri Potemkine, spokesman for the Union of Democratic Forces, a heterogeneous grouping of twelve parties.
“It’s a cosmetic change,” said Alexandre Milinkievitch, a former opposition presidential candidate from 2006 and leader of the pro-European movement, “because the important thing is who counts the voices, and with us, it’s the executive branch.
If members of the opposition enter parliament, they will have been appointed, not elected.
But their entry into parliament can mean space on television, meetings in the regions, and bills.”
The opposition must therefore enter the political game because "the dialogue with the European Union must begin.
Because if our economy, which is heavily indebted to Russia, goes into crisis, and we don’t reform ourselves, we risk becoming a protectorate of Russia.
We want to be independent.”
The opposition fears that the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe that followed the electoral process will not recognize the validity of the ballot.
She stresses that the turnout figures seem too high, and that the generalization of early voting (26% of voters in Minsk) has opened the door to all manipulations.
“Have you noticed that there was an election, you?” asked Social Democratic leader Alexandre Kozouline, one of the last two political prisoners released in August of this year.
There was no one in the polling stations.
And there will be a maximum of five opposition MPs in parliament, those who are best suited to power.”
The silence of the night falls back on the square of October.
On television, President Lukashenko and members of the Central Electoral Commission welcome their success.
The Interview - Blood is Safe Again
Héma-Québec was celebrating the 10th anniversary of its founding yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, as Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And most importantly, it regained the public trust that had been seriously shaken by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood supply managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service was contaminated with acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
Faced with this tragedy and public grudge, the Government of Canada instituted in February 1994 a public inquiry, presided over by Judge Horace Krever, to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations that such a disaster should not happen again.
While Judge Krever was delaying in filing his report, some provinces set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Services to supply all other provinces and two territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its activities, only 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec," recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Through efforts to improve the safety of blood and work products in the field during the years that followed, we regained public confidence," she said, adding that in early 2008, nearly 94% of the Quebec population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps in mind that “trust is something extremely fragile.”
From its inception, on September 28, 1998, Héma-Québec applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, there were many cases in Europe of the human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, tells the story of the one that has held the fort since its foundation in 1998.
"And we didn't know at all if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
We then relied on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gelineau reports, according to which when it is not known and that a serious disease may result, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain inevitably leading to death, exclusion measures are introduced.
In April 1999, the blood of people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980 was refused.
A few years ago, it was clear that the disease was spread through the blood.
This episode showed us that the precautionary principle we applied made sense."
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV testing technique appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests (NTAs) that directly detect the presence of the virus itself in the blood of donors and not that of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used until then were based.
TANs have shortened the silent period, which stretches from when the person was infected to when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
This period could be reduced to less than a week.
This has substantially reduced the risk that some donors are unknowingly infected and cannot be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
“In other words, it means you’ll have to distribute 12 million blood products before someone is infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of transmission of HIV by a blood product occurs.
I believe we can now feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover our health," said Héma-Québec's Chief Executive Officer.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
Just last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect into the bloodstream.
We must be constantly vigilant," continues Dr. Décary, before stressing that in addition to a secure supply, Héma-Québec must also provide for an adequate supply.
“The needs are increasing because the population is getting older.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need refills in red blood cells or platelets.
The aging of the population also has consequences for the blood donor network, which on average represents only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation."
Healthy people 18 years of age and older who meet the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer their blood are not accepted because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a malaria-ridden country, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
“With these 3%, we are able to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Scarcity is very rare.
But the members of this donor network must be renewed as they get older and can no longer donate their blood.
It is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to hold them back and encourage them to become regular donors.
Because today’s life is so unbridled, we rarely find time to spend an hour giving of our blood,” says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec provides not only blood products, but also human tissue, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for heavy burns.
These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered a biomedical waste is full of blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“A few weeks ago, we celebrated the banking of our thousandth cord blood sample and we plan to take more than a thousand a year.
We should start proposing transplants early next year,” says Dr. Décary, who describes the cord blood sampling program as very popular.
"Several mothers are disappointed that they cannot access them," because Héma-Québec does not have the means to offer this complex and costly program in every hospital in Quebec.
