Charest on the North
The Prime Minister does not rule out triggering elections before the end of the year
As soon as the general council of the Liberal Party was finished, Jean Charest visited yesterday Jean-Talon, in Quebec, where the new Minister of Health, Yves Bolduc (left), tries to get elected on the occasion of today's by-election.
"Strengthening the limits of our last great northern border": this is the long-term ambition that Jean Charest presented visually while remaining broadly speaking, at the end of the General Council of the Liberal Party of Quebec, in Lévis, yesterday.
Behind him, during his speech, was projected a kind of Mill of images.
On three huge screens, spectacular shots of hydroelectric dams, mining, Quebec seen by Google Maps, maps, etc. were filmed in a loop.
Big money, just like during elections.
At the press briefing, the Prime Minister refused to rule out that he would trigger the election this fall, even though he pointed out that his schedule was very busy.
The "Plan Nord" is the fourth part of a "vision" that the Prime Minister claims to have for Quebec, that of a "new economic space", which includes an agreement on the workforce with France, an agreement between Canada and Europe and agreements with Ontario.
Often mentioned in the speeches of the Prime Minister recently, the opening of the North - the northern territory at 49th parallel - had never been the subject of a presentation.
The Prime Minister, however, limited himself to explaining why the North was "a jewel of immense potential", but did not give a deadline, investment amounts, or specific priority in future projects.
At most there are a few avenues for further development: hydropower, forestry, but above all the mining sector, boosted by the growth of emerging countries and the reconstruction of public infrastructure.
The North contains "nickel, zinc, copper, platinum, gold, silver, iron, titanium, and even diamond," according to the enumeration of Mr. Charest.
This "territory twice as big as France", "it's home, it's in Quebec.
Not only is it home, but it is in us,” he insisted, as if to show that he was soliciting a national founding myth.
Quebec has built up a lot in its relationship with the North, he stressed: the gold rush in Abitibi, Quebec engineering, James Bay.
“It’s ours, it’s our future,” he added, after taking a theatrical break to contemplate the huge map behind him.
The North, 70% of Quebec's territory, includes a portion of Labrador that Quebec has always claimed, the prime minister said at the news briefing.
“This is a traditional position that all governments have reiterated.
There is a border line on which there has been no agreement for a very long time and, when the opportunity arises, I reiterate that position on behalf of the government,” he said.
“With climate change, we need to rethink our vision of the North,” he said, referring to the Northwest Passage, which will open year-round due to melting ice.
In this new geopolitical context, the Prime Minister believes that occupying the territory is a duty.
What about the inhabitants of the territory, First Nations and Inuit?
The Prime Minister said that the Quebec government would be very attentive to them and that the project would benefit them, especially young people.
Two former ministers from two different parties, Pierre Corbeil and Michel Létourneau (former Pequiste member of Ungava), have already begun consultations with about thirty communities.
An interministerial committee chaired by Benoît Pelletier, in which Julie Boulet (Transport and Natural Resources) has an important place, has begun work.
The prime minister does not rule out a big meeting, "not necessarily a summit", but a moment when "we will give ourselves a common vision".
The development of the North would be in accordance with the principles of sustainable development.
The North Plan will be "concert, orderly and environmentally friendly," he said.
Jean Charest described this "vision" as being in continuity with that of the Liberal prime minister who preceded it.
“Like the Liberals before us, we have thought differently to turn challenges into new opportunities for growth and development.”
This was also one of the recurring themes of the weekend, which began on Friday with a big cocktail to mark the 50th anniversary of Jean Lesage’s arrival at the head of the party.
One of the resolutions adopted proposes to rename the Beauharnois Power Station to Adélard-Godbout Dam.
“From Godbout, who created Hydro-Québec, to Lesage, who made the Quiet Revolution and the nationalization of hydroelectricity, to Bourassa, who made James Bay, our party has forged the future,” Charest said.
As a point of press, he invoked another conservative reference, John Diefenbaker's "Roads to the North" program, prime minister from 1957 to 1963.
Addressing the Eastmain1a-Ruper hydroelectric dam project, Mr. Charest stressed that its commissioning was planned for 2012.
“It stays between us there, but I plan to be there,” he told his activists, eliciting cheerful applause at home.
Indeed, the Prime Minister, who said in April that there would be no elections in 2008 and probably not in 2009, did not rule out the possibility of triggering a vote this fall, which the law allows him.
He points out that his schedule is filled, however, notably by a mission of the Federation Council in China and a Quebec-New York summit.
The weekend’s General Council provided the Liberal leader with a platform containing nationalist resolutions, including “constitutional aspirations” that are passed as a letter to the post: the PLQ calls in particular for recognition of the “specificity of Quebec” in the Constitution.
He also hoped that Quebec would appoint members of the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission and that they would have a veto over the decisions taken in Quebec.
On the opposition side, the broad outlines of the Northern Plan were met with skepticism.
The chief fisherman, Pauline Marois, highlighted the Nord-du-Québec Development Policy that the Landry government launched in 2001.
According to her, the Liberal government, when it came to power in 2003, gave up on applying it.
If he had done so, "we would have been more advanced today" commented Ms. Marois alongside her candidate in Jean-Talon (voting that takes place today), Françoise Mercure.
ADQ said it supports the government's adoption of a Northern Plan.
“But what we want is that it’s not just a show,” said leader Sébastien Proulx, replacing Mario Dumont, who is returning from vacation today.
Letters - A Dishonored Country
It was Mr. Vic Toews, former Minister of Justice (or irony) in the Harper cabinet, who last summer allowed himself to say of Louise Arbour that she was a "shame" for Canada.
To cast reproach on this woman who has waged a relentless struggle for justice and who deserves our admiration says as much about the Prime Minister's entourage as about Stephen Harper himself.
We are facing a government that is the only one, among all the Western countries involved, that has not repatriated its national locked up in the Guantánamo concentration camp.
A government that does not take into account the fact that Omar Khadr was a very young teenager at the time of the facts that are being blamed on him.
The only government that, despite the fact that Canada has signed the Geneva Convention, denies its word and allows a child soldier to be killed in inhumane conditions.
The only one who relies on a parody of justice to assess the guilt of the accused.
Recall, for example, that UNICEF, Amnesty International and the Canadian Bar Association are advocating for the repatriation of Omar Khadr for a fair trial in Canada.
It is this same government that turns a blind eye to torture: it doesn’t matter if a young adult is now psychologically destroyed, probably forever after so many years of exactions.
We are not yet aware of it, but we are witnessing at this moment an insidious erosion of our rights, our freedom and our "democracy", the word that Harper keeps brandishing and that sounds so hollow in his mouth.
The time has come when there is no morality anymore: one can mishandle, torture, arbitrarily imprison a Canadian citizen according to the goodwill of a head of government so far a minority (what will be after October 14...).
Many voters believe that they will find salvation in a party that advocates the Virtue, the Law and the Order: they do not see that this government has renounced what made our country's reputation and dignity.
Shame, Mr. Toews, is there, in this resignation, and nowhere else.
Free Opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Speech
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Patrick J. Garver, Executive Vice President of Canadian Mining Barrick Gold.
Following an Orwellian logic, he claims that the world’s largest gold company has filed a six-million-dollar defamation lawsuit against three authors and a small, penniless publishing house with the aim of launching a “transparent public debate.”
While it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of defamation proceedings, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely obscured by Mr. Garver.
Because, for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to bring to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and publisher of the book Black Canada will have to spend considerable sums in preparation for their defense and to fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of the mine.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose an amicable settlement that will gag the opposition in addition to frightening anyone who dares to look back at the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was in front of the public that she should have presented her view of the facts.
Contrary to what is done in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are normally conducted through the exchange of ideas and not with batons.
It was enough for the miner to open his books, his files and establish a real debate, through the newspapers, the media, the publications and the funding of independent research teams that could have made light of the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to trust public opinion and rejects petitions and letters of support to the authors of Noir Canada.
Perhaps Mr. Garver could explain how he can both demand a "public" debate while contempt for the views of that same audience?
In the world of the Vice-President, it seems that this word refers only to lawyers who are overpaid and not all Canadians; this is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democracy, even critics have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn't understand, or doesn't want to understand, is that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada does so primarily because it rejects the brutal way of mining.
This audience is ready to hear Barrick and to judge, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, and not as part of what many perceive as a gag suit (following the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just filed a formal notice to the authors of Noir Canada urging them to cease using the term...).
Beyond Mr. Garver’s surreal discourse, Barrick Gold’s prosecution is a direct attack on the freedom of academic research and the quest for truth, essential to any democratic society.
It denies, as a whole, the right to quote from credible sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which represent the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss issues that are displeasing to the rich companies of this world in a country like Canada, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, he could do so by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
She has a right of reply.
The academic community, to which we belong, has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s disproportionate prosecution makes it clear that, contrary to what she claims, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss for academia, as it is for public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place mechanisms to limit such abusive prosecutions.
Wall Street Rescue - Democrats and Republicans Agree
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republican and Democratic, finally came to an agreement yesterday on the biggest economic bailout since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has shaken Wall Street for months is yet to be endorsed by both houses of Congress.
It includes: better monitoring by elected officials of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for failure to pay, as well as a right to look at the salaries paid to the managers of the companies rescued.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news minutes after midnight yesterday, after a two-day negotiation marathon.
“We have made great progress toward an agreement that will be effective in the markets,” said Bush administration Representative Henry Paulson.
“Everything has been done in a way that protects the real economy and ordinary Americans from the ongoing crisis on Wall Street,” she said.
“That’s the fundamental point: if we don’t do that, the trauma, chaos and disruption to Americans’ daily lives will be immense,” said Rep. Judd Gregg.
Negotiations had turned to sprint in recent hours for fear of the effect a new failure would have on investors’ moods.
The time limit we agreed to was the opening of the markets this morning.
Lately associated with the negotiations, the two candidates in the U.S. presidential election have been rather supportive of the agreement, while expressing their dissatisfaction that we are forced to reach this extreme.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has claimed to have added some provisions to the agreement, including allowing homeowners to keep their homes and allowing them to keep their salaries on the salaries of the executives of the companies that have been rescued by the state.
“When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary action because of the irresponsibility of some, there is nothing to be congratulated on.
But these measures are necessary," he said on U.S. television.
Asked on another channel whether he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied: "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
“The outlines I’ve read [show] that it’s something that we’re all going to have to digest and that we’re going to be able to move forward with.
The option of doing nothing is simply not acceptable,” he said.
The $700 billion plan aims to buy back with taxpayers’ money the dubious, risky and unsold debts of U.S. financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the bursting of a real estate bubble that first led to the collapse of risky mortgages (subprimes) before expanding to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAA) and leading to a freeze of liquidity and the banishment of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republicans who overturned the first draft agreement last week.
It is believed to have come out of this deadlock since Democrats accepted that some “toxic” assets of struggling companies are only insured by the government, rather than bought.
In order to round the corners for everyone in Congress, a provision was also added stating that if the government were to assume losses for five years with this program, it could put in place new taxes to help it recover its stake.
The new plan provides for a first tranche of $250 billion, plus $100 billion if the president deems it necessary.
The payment of another $350 billion is expected to be endorsed by another Congressional vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will get stakes in rescued companies that will earn him dividends in the event of a profit and that he can resell when the turmoil is over.
The federal government will have the opportunity to delay the seizure procedures for housing related to the real estate loans covered by this plan, as well as to set limits on the pay and severance pay paid to the managers of the affected companies.
The plan's architects would like to see it put to the House vote today, and the Senate vote Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will have the green light.
Yesterday, votes continued to rise against this bill, both in the Republican and Democratic camps.
“Obviously, Washington doesn’t hear you,” Republican House Finance Committee member Scott Garrett told voters.
“Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not for the benefit of taxpayers.”
Host of a small group in Congress dubbed “the caucus of skeptics,” Democratic Rep. Brad Sherman presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred eminent professors of economics, including three Nobel laureates, have written to us to tell us: we are asking Congress not to rush and to carefully consider the way forward,” he said.
At the same time, in Europe, there was once again proof of the global nature of the crisis.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion US).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg was made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was giving up on acquiring its competitor in full shipwreck since it lost 2 billion euros (2.9 billion US) in the crisis of risky real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the top 20 European banks and top 10 insurers.
"This is not lost money," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said.
In exchange, a right to vote in the bank and influence is recovered.
This is precisely something that savers and households appreciate now that times are proving uncertain.”
Meanwhile, on the other side of the English Channel, the British government seemed on track to nationalize another bank battered by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over all the loans in progress at Bradford and Bringley, including more than 41 billion ($75.5 billion) of real estate loans.
Spanish bank Santander said yesterday it would buy the UK bank’s branches and customer accounts.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, that the British government should nationalize since the beginning of this financial crisis.
