What could Zuschlag Company do in their invoice factory?
Soon, on 8 October, the hearings related to the current criminal procedure will begin, against János Zuschlag and his accomplices.
The politician and his accomplices are charged with fraud, in the form of a criminal organization, on a permanent and regular basis, resulting in particularly significant damages, and other charges have been brought against them, such as forgery and the use of forgeries.
According to the prosecutor's office, the money from grants was spent for personal purposes, while the benefits were justified by false invoices.
The money from the state and municipalities, about 65 million HUF in total, went to the coffers of the Fiatal Baloldal movement on the one hand and to the pockets of some people on the other.
Their method, also made public by the investigating authorities, was to receive money from the grants obtained by issuing invoices for expenses, behind which no actual services were provided and thus, the associations never fulfilled their commitments.
According to the indictment, much of the invoices were forged.
For the latter, they procured invoice books at the Józsefváros market, while they manufactured the stamps in Kiskunhalas.
For the names of companies that would appear on the invoices, it was decided, among other things, during the tours in the northern province of Lake Balaton, carried out by István Lados, at the request of János Zuschlag.
According to the testimony of the latter, he had to locate pensions and restaurants.
For his personal consumption, he requested an invoice, on the model of which they made the other invoices that they were going to introduce, among others, to the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, as well as the Municipality of the Capital to access subsidies.
The majority of the invoices were created by István Lados and his accomplice András ?ri, who according to our information, was mainly concerned with drafting the files necessary to obtain the grants.
During a "tracking circuit", one of Lados's choices was a bistro.
According to the two invoices issued by the Zuschlag in 2003, this place has been responsible for the restoration of a group of 90 people, members of the association Biztos Pont Egyesület.
However, according to the manager, it would have been impossible for so many people to occupy this place at the same time.
Similarly, in the summer of 2002, the invoice drawn up in the name of the Jobb Jövért Foundation, which would later bear the name Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért, was full of errors of form and substance.
A guesthouse in Badacsonytomaj actually had only three rooms, and a maximum of ten people could stay overnight, yet the bill mentioned one hundred and thirty guests.
The issuers of invoices with the overflowing imagination also fell into excess, when they mentioned the company Pigal Kft, also belonging to the Horeca sector. In their accounts, neither the name of Jobb Jövért nor that of the Hoppa appeared, according to the information given to the prosecutor's office.
The company's manager, Gyoz Farkas, told hvg.hu that when the prosecutor's office summoned him and showed him the invoices, he immediately knew it was fake documents.
“Our company name and tax number were placed in the wrong place on the stamp.”
He added: "Beyond the form, the fact that according to the invoice, a hundred people stayed there, was also not suitable, since this establishment has only eleven rooms, which do not have as much space.
In addition, the invoice also mentions meals, and our restaurant has been closed for a long time."
The issuers of zealous invoices also did not inquire about the Budapest travel agencies, which were part of their choice, but only organized trips abroad. Thus, naively, they indicated stays in Hungary on invoices to be paid in cash, which also goes against the accounting practices of the agency.
Moreover, as the survey showed, they also added VAT on these documents, while services relating to travel activities, whose destination is outside the European Union, are invoiced without VAT.
Similarly, the VAT rate of the four invoices drawn up in the name of the Hotel Revfülöp at the order of Jobb Jövért was incorrect, since the company's services do not support a VAT of 25% as indicated, but a VAT of 15%. In addition, the hotel employees issue only printed invoices, while the fakes were handwritten.
The prosecutor's investigation reveals that the "issuers" also made mistakes in referring as a service to the transport of goods by road, which the invoice issuing company could not exercise, since its profile was investment advice.
In addition, it is also due to defects of form, such as inadequate types of invoices and false stamps, that the invoices issued to the order of Együtt to Harmadik Evezredert Alapítvány, of XXI.
As in the case of the company Ravenna Bt. or the Kunfehértó sports workshop, both of which deny that they are the authors of the invoices issued on their behalf.
Nor did the forgers pay attention to the fact that the company HIB Kft., based in Nyíregyháza, was in liquidation at the time (in 2001) the group of Fiatal Városért Egyesület was supposed to have a meal at their house.
Deliberately established invoices
Another category of invoice issuers is those who were fully aware that they were being asked to issue fictitious invoices.
The Esély Budapestért Alapítvány Foundation, at the request of the Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták grouping, has drawn up an invoice to the Együtt Foundation to Harmadik Évezredért, for an amount of four million HUF.
According to the indictment, the manager of the company Collab Kft. was led to issue false invoices by one of the accused, Ludovic Györfi.
Likewise, it cooperated with the Zuschlags, the company Biogate Kft., which is currently in liquidation and which in 2003 issued invoices to the Jobb Jövért Alapítvány Foundation, the Atlasz Egyesület Association and the Vorösfeny-Egyesület Association, for an amount of about five million HU.
No financial movement took place, either, as the invoices issued were later cancelled, but the agencies avoided mentioning it in their accounts.
The next category of invoice issuing companies is those directly related to the accused.
For example, the administrative representative of the managing director of Delta Trió Kft., dealing with the trade in fuel and motor vehicles, whose head office was in Budapest, but where it was not found, was Iván Kubatov.
In October, November and December 2005, this company issued several invoices for the sale of IT equipment, amounting to approximately HUF 18 million.
According to the investigation, the equipment was purchased by the company Cash Investment Kft. de Kiskunhalas, which had been in liquidation since 14 September 2005.
The director of the company was a man of Romanian origin, to whom Ivan Kubatov also allegedly sent documents related to the company, between 2002 and 2005.
As far as we know, Kubatov acknowledged during the investigation that he issued invoices to Atlasz, Hoppa and Együtt companies to Harmadik Évezredért Alapitvány, and that he pocketed their countervalue.
It was precisely at the request of Ivan Kubatov that Romanian Masons created the companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt.
In reality, none of these companies worked, which the accused explained by the fact that they were not receiving work.
He still used these companies, since at the request of Master Zsolt Szente, co-accused and editor of the founding documents of the companies, he established invoices to their names, to the order of associations related to Zuschlag, such as the associations Atlasz and Y-Generació.
Kubatov donated 15 invoices in total to organizations issued by Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, worth HUF 14.2 million.
The prosecutor’s office thought that 10% of the sums shown on the invoices and VAT were in Kubatov’s pocket.
The man even used the company Szi-Beri Bt. to establish fictitious invoices that were used as part of Biztos Pont’s grant application.
In January 2006, the Association Y-Generáció and Szövetség a Modern Magyarországért submitted a grant application to the Socialist Party's public utility, Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (TMA).
They received this grant for an amount of twice 500,000 HUF, but these amounts were not used for the purposes indicated in the application.
To prevent this from becoming known, five fictitious invoices received from Works Team Kft. were presented at the TMA.
Moreover, it is these invoices that were found during the search carried out in the office of Árpád Kemecsei, in the Ministry of Education.
At the hearing, some of the defendants will report on the method of making the invoices, as they had previously done before the prosecution.
What could be really interesting would be that the main defendant, János Zuschlag himself, decides to lift the veil over the whole story.
So far, his confessions are not very detailed, and although he has repeatedly promised to tell the smallest details, he has not yet done so.
The question is whether it is in his interest, or perhaps the Socialists would have reached an agreement according to which, in exchange for the reimbursement of a large part of the 50 million HUF, Zusi would wear the hat alone.
Today, the latter is probably vexed, as applications for his supervised residency, based on a relief of his conditions of detention, continually fall into the ears of a deaf person.
While those who have caused much greater damage, and the perpetrators of non-reparable economic crimes, walk around freely or at least wait at their own home for the end of the procedure.
The Psychology of Overbidding: Why Do We Spend More Money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the merchandise.
New York University neurology and economics researchers have managed to update the neurological and economic bases of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, human beings do not want to be distanced during this type of competition, such as an auction on eBay, and that is why they even prefer to pay a high price.
This research has attempted to draw a neurological pattern of this kind of "game" using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, while the other group took part in a playful auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) process, the researchers analyzed the active brain domains of the experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could earn money, but during the auction, an essential element of which is a third-party overselling, the whole under the brainstem, called the striatum, was moving intensely when the game was lost.
This part of the brain, along with several other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of "self-stimulation" of the nervous system.
That is why, according to the researchers, the rise in prices can be explained by the flight in the face of the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, the economists of this group of researchers continued financial surveillance analyses.
At the time, three groups were bidding against a partner in various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and thus made their bet.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they would come out winning the game, then they would receive an additional $15 as a reward.
While the third group received this $15 before the auctions, the group members also lost that money, in case they lost the auctions.
The difference between these two groups is in fact that the focus was in one group on victory, while in the other, on failure.
Proving the neurologists' hypothesis, members of the players' team "against failure" were willing to bet higher than those made by the control group and the group "for victory".
“These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
Indeed, each of them explained the phenomena observed during auctions only by the pleasure of winning and the parade before the risk.
Only methods of neurological imaging have helped to remove the contradiction between the two theories by now leading to a third explanation." - noted Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economics at New York University.
Hepatitis: When should we see a doctor?
Worldwide, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary, chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
There are an estimated one hundred thousand patients carrying the hepatitis virus in Hungary, but only seven miles are being treated, which is because patients often do not know that they are carriers of the virus.
Hepatitis is a generic name given to infections that affect the liver and are caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but the pathogens and diseases generated differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, depending on the pathogenic genes, spread mainly in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travelers, it is recommended that they get vaccinated against viruses A and B. There is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating contaminated foods, usually accompanied by poor general condition, weakness, stomach aches and nausea.
Then develops on the skin and on the white of the eye a visible jaundice, the stools become lighter and the urine takes a darker color. Healing can take two to three weeks.
Every year around the world, one million people die of the most serious form of this pathology, such as cancer or liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten patients receive medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients are not known to have the virus, because the pathogenic gene deceptively destroys liver cells. In many cases, the first symptoms appear only after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
Contamination is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people who underwent blood transfusions before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
Currently, there are 200 million patients with chronic type C hepatitis worldwide.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult your treating doctor as soon as you observe symptoms of unknown origin.
The disease can be cured, if it is detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, in this way the risk of infection disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized in 2004 by organizations representing patients from all over the world.
Its goal is to draw attention to chronic cirrhosis of the liver, caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Does one who believes in God feel less pain?
According to the results of a recent research, religious belief would function as a kind of analgesic, which would already have contributed to making the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
The British daily Telegraph published an article that researchers at the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment by analyzing at what level belief in God could influence human pain tolerance.
In the context of this at least bizarre experiment, 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists were subjected to electroshocks, while each of them was observing a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to rule out much of the suffering.
Through a technique of palpation of the human brain, it has also been discovered that Catholics have been able to activate the part of their brain responsible for regulating pain.
This analysis is the first in a series of experiments, in which academics, scholars, philosophers and theologians participate from different sectors of the university.
More precisely, the experiment takes place in the following way: an instrument emitting sparks and diffusing electroshocks is fixed on the left hand of the experimental subject.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to look closely at two paintings, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Hermine Lady painted by Leonardo da Vinci in the 15th century.
The researchers behind this experiment hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary evokes a kind of state of faith among believers, while the choice of Da Vinci's painting, not very different from the first, focused on its soothing effect.
The experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and meanwhile, received 20 electroshocks in four parts in succession, while looking either at religious-themed or more general-themed painting.
Catholics said that at the sight of the Virgin Mary, they felt like they were “safe,” like someone “taken care of,” and they “calmed down, and peace invaded them.”
At the sight of the religious-themed painting, they reported 12% less pain than when they were looking at Leonardo's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the experiment, believes that the same effects can be achieved with any other strong image, in atheists, provided that the appropriate photo is found.
“We should find a picture they react to very positively, like a mother or father,” he said.
Tom Wright, Anglican bishop, welcomed the results of this research.
“The practice of faith should change, and in many cases, it actually changes our personality,” Wright added.
After these excellent results, there remains only the question of what would be the effect on the regulation of the pain of the subjects if the believers were shown a Madonna painted by Leonardo or by a painter of the same caliber?
Would the sight of a better Virgin Mary produce better results?
You are what you reveal about yourself.
On the occasion of his tenth birthday, Google says that he can be found at the bottom of people’s pockets just like the sky above their heads. He knows where they spent their holidays, which specialists they consult and what their interests are.
But that’s not enough, according to Eric Schmidt, who is one of the most influential people in society.
While skeptics draw parallels to Orwell’s horror vision, they just don’t see the essence of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google’s main ambition is to gather even more information about its users. This is necessary so that Google’s founders can meet their initial goal that sounded like: “Let’s collect all the information in a system in the world!”.
According to the Google executive interviewed, after ten years of work of global upheaval, they are still only at the beginning of their goals to be able to process all the information.
Schmidt replied that he would like Google to be able to answer questions like "What could I do tomorrow?" or "What job would I do best?" However, software will only be able to answer this kind of question, simple at first glance, when they know enough about users.
It is not entirely clear to all internet users that the words used during internet searches, the IP address of the computer that launches the search and the pages visited by the interested parties are precisely listed.
Through the Personalized Search program launched two years ago, users can, for example, store their own search history and can view what they searched for, what they clicked on. Thanks to this, in the long term, Recommendations, program based on the same logic, will be able to give much more personalized answers, and we will submit products and services based on our previous statements and preferences.
What happens if someone uses my data against me, if they look at what my job is? ask users, who worry seeing Google's information monopoly.
In most cases, it is the potential power represented by society that can arouse fear, and it is not remorse, the fear of punishment, the desire for freedom or possibly the revolt against power that can arouse a counter-reaction among Internet users.
It is a confirmed fact, however, that the search terms are not only registered, but in justified cases, they are passed on to a third party, and in this kind of legal case, nothing protects the personal rights of Internet users.
The most striking example of recent times is probably the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, during which Google transmitted to the Brazilian government the information it had collected on the public page called Orkut, thus allowing identification.
Human rights-conscious Internet users were able to breathe a sigh of relief last May, when Google, arm in arm with the electronic legal protection agency EFF, proved its right in court to the FBI. According to the ruling, in the future, Google will still not be able to be forced by any of the points in the constitution to disclose information on the FBI’s secret application of any kind.
(At the same time, the federal government successfully obtained some 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms it had won over the strengthening of the Child Protection Act, passed several years earlier. But ultimately, it failed to procure the lists of private users' searches, or the entire list of websites and keywords from the past two months.)
Google’s judgment is therefore quite contradictory: it is harassed by those who fear the transmission of their personal data, because they think that their intimate sphere and private domain suffer from it when they start using Google services. Therefore, they attack them in the spirit of revolt against multinational companies proud of their conservative image.
