The smart car imitates the robbery of the bumblebee
What better method would be used to develop technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle than the imitation of an existing obstacle detector in nature?
For example, the bee.
In the amazing project presented at CEATEC, taking place in Japan, buzzing bees gave Nissan engineers the starting strategic idea, to inspire them on how they must design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan built a mini-robot car, a bio-inspired self-control system, type BR23C, which it equipped with the qualities of bees, the end goal being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee forms its own oval-shaped space, which in reality looks a lot like our secure protective shell - explained, during the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the research and development and public relations technology department of the brand.
The bee’s faceted eye plays a key role, as it is able to see in all directions, at an angle of 300 degrees.
To mimic the functions of the faceted eye, engineers approached the idea of the laser rangefinder.
It identifies obstacles at a 180-degree angle and at a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, evaluates distances and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which transforms it into an avoidance maneuver right away.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second, then the mini-auto robot, mimicking the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it by an angle sufficient to avoid collision.
Unlike any existing system, this avoidance manoeuvre takes place entirely instinctively.
“If it wasn’t, the mini-auto robot wouldn’t be able to react quickly enough to avoid the hurdle,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and Robotic Car Project.
It must react instinctively and instantly, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the protective envelope, a layer where for now the collision is considered inevitable.
This whole process should reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in the blink of an eye.
Contrary to bees, the difference cannot go upwards, downwards or diagonally, it can only be of two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can turn.
In this way, instead of the endless combinations that bees have to avoid other bees, in our case, we could only use the rotary movement, acceleration as well as slowing down as maneuvers available to the mini auto robot
The BR23C uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy concentration, which makes their life longer than in the lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the instinctive intelligent reaction that is paramount, not the processing of data, let alone the ability to store.
This mechanism must process only a few incoming signals per second, and react to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with intuitive logic based on the data of previous maneuvers, in this way it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of continuous memory.
You don't need memory of a gigabyte capacity, or even megabytes.
This is the first step towards the design of a technology used for instant avoidance. According to Nissan estimates, this system will enter mass-produced cars in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination avoiding obstacles in his way.
