The written version of the $700 billion economic bailout, aimed at buying back the banks’ dubious credits, and using them in multiples, is ready.
In the first round, half of that amount will be spent.
Reuters reports that during new debates that lasted until after midnight on Saturday, Congressional leaders agreed on controversies that had existed for days and days, around the $700 billion bailout plan.
“We’ve taken a serious step forward,” said Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic president of the U.S. House of Representatives, who said the deal was only to be put on paper.
The compromise, born out of the plan, is supported by the two presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson commented on the results of the compromise that the program will work and be effective, but other measures still need to be implemented. According to Pelosi, it is not about saving Wall Street here, but about turning the wheels of the economy in the other direction.
The written version of the plan was made public prior to the opening of Asian markets on Sunday evening at 8 p.m. local Washington time (i.e. Monday at 2 a.m., depending on local Central European time), but did not cause a dramatic rise in stock markets.
On Monday, the House of Representatives will be the first to vote on the 2008 Emergency Economic Stabilization Act, and then its fate will be in the hands of the Senate.
On Saturday night, President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi, then the White House also welcomed the news of the deal.
"We are pleased with the progress made tonight, and we greatly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy," White House spokesman Tony Fratto said.
In addition, the program diverges from the initial proposal made by the Bush administration, which mentioned that the $700 billion should be spent at once, for the purchase of securities with doubtful credits.
From now on, a maximum of half of the $700 billion can be spent. The first $250 billion will be issued immediately after Congress passed the bill, probably Monday. This first sum will be used by the Secretary of the Treasury to buy up doubtful claims from banks, while the use of the additional $100 billion will be left to the discretion of the President.
The program will be overseen by an independent body, in which the President of the Federal Reserve will also take part.
The spending of the second half of the $700 billion depends on a new congressional decree.
Under the law, the Treasury Secretariat will be able to put in place a combined strategy: at the same time, it will be able to buy dubious claims, securities related to dubious mortgages and mortgages, as well as other types of "toxic" claims.
The department's competent persons stated that the purchases can take place as part of an auction, but also directly.
The rule allows the companies involved to take part in an insurance program, where the Treasury Secretariat guarantees the tools that cause the concerns, for which the companies will have paid a premium equivalent to the foreseeable damage.
Henry Paulson said the law provides the tools needed to allocate $700 billion for the urgent needs of the financial system, whether it’s the extensive redemption of dubious claims, their insurance, or avoiding the risk of the system collapsing any major financial institution.
“We will take the necessary steps to be prepared for the law as soon as it is signed,” he added.
On the other hand, bank managers who are in a bad position and are waiting for state aid can expect their severance pay, simply called gold parachute across the Atlantic, to be capped by the government.
Wage caps are only mentioned in specific cases, and limitations depend on how the Treasury Secretariat offers assistance to the business.
The cap principle means that if the Treasury Secretariat buys back as part of an auction, they will levy a surcharge on the gold parachute, unless the discredited bank president retires.
Directly after the purchase of the dubious debts, the government will intervene aggressively to ensure that the amount paid to the leaders is not overstated.
For the image to be complete, it must still be added that the existing golden parachutes are not modified. The cap only concerns the new contracts, this to motivate participation in the plan.
“This is the first time in U.S. history that legal caps will be in place on Directors General’s appointments,” said Barney Frank, chairman of the House Financial Benefits Committee.
In addition, the government acquires the right to acquire shares in the banks participating in the plan, which reduces the risk of taxpayers, since they can even win in the case as soon as the economy and with it the rescued banks fall back on their feet.
The bill mentions that within the next five years, the President must submit a proposal to Congress that will rule on how losses will be returned to taxpayers, starting from the financial sector.
On both sides, there were obviously those who expressed their doubts about this plan.
That’s not why U.S. citizens have mandated us, it doesn’t protect taxpayer dollars,” said Rep. Darrell Issa.
