Industrial prices continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 percent compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 percent compared to the month of August 2007 - reports the Central Statistical Office of Hungary.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1 percent compared to July 2008, while compared to a year earlier, they decreased by 3.9 percent.
As a result of fluctuations in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to the previous month and by 3.2 per cent compared to the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices increased only to a lesser extent: by 0.1 percent, compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industry sectors rose only a tiny 0.1 per cent compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 per cent), with, first, the manufacture of bags and belts with a monthly increase of 4.6 per cent, then the production of shoes with a 2.5 per cent monthly increase.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical and manufacturing sector (1.6 per cent).
This resulted in deflation in the oil processing sector (1.4 per cent), the manufacture of electrical machinery and appliances (0.9 per cent), as well as a minimal increase in the wood processing sector (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing have not changed.
Other sectors of the processing industry saw an increase, ranging from 0.2 per cent to 0.9 per cent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, which play a significant role in domestic industrial operations, prices rose 0.3 percent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in the price of gas implemented by the authorities since July 1.
In a twelve-month comparison, taking into account the domestic sales of the processing sectors, it was the prices of the oil processing sector that saw the most significant increase (32.4 percent).
In the metallurgical manufacturing sector, prices increased by 13.2 per cent, while in the important food, beverage and tobacco sectors, prices increased by 11 per cent.
Price decreases occurred in the textile and textile production sectors (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacturing of electrical machinery and appliances (0.3 per cent).
In other sectors of the processing industry, the price increase varied between 0.6 percent and 9.1 percent.
Throughout the processing industry, prices increased by 10.2 per cent over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors exceeded the previous year's prices by 18.7 per cent.
Among the domestic trade groups and according to the allocation of sectors, in August, it was the sectors initiators of profit on investment that showed the most significant monthly price increase (0.7 percent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while in the energy and material sectors for further processing there was no change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, there was the largest increase in the energy and material sectors for further processing (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, inflation was measured at 6.8 per cent, while in the profit-initiating sectors, inflation was measured at 1.4 per cent.
Export prices in the industrial sector, in HUF, rose 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, while they fell 3.9 percent over 12 months.
In one month, our national payment method weakened by 1.7 per cent against the euro, and by 7.1 per cent against the dollar. Compared with August 2007, it strengthened by 7.5 per cent against the euro and 15.9 per cent against the dollar.
