Járóka said: The vicious circle of poverty and segregation must be broken
Today, in Paris, the European Summit for Equal Opportunities began, hosted by France, as the representative of the current Presidency of the European Union.
In her message to the plenary, as one of the main spokesmen of the expert consultation, Livia Járóka, MEP Fidesz European People's Party, drew attention to segregation in education, because it is a violation of the right that most affects Roma children and therefore, one of the main barriers to their success in life.
On behalf of the French Presidency, this high-level conference was opened by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Labour and Social Affairs, and by Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Labour, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
Among those invited to participate in the consultation are the European social partners, as well as the most eminent representatives of legal protection and European civil bodies, in the field of equal opportunities.
According to the press office of the Fidesz People's Party group, Járóka warned that alongside the distinctions seen during the hirings, Roma disappear from the labour market, first of all, due to their low qualifications.
"An overwhelming majority of young Roma do not have high school degrees, and as a result of poor elementary education, only a tiny fraction has the opportunity to earn a graduate degree."
Furthermore, Járóka stressed that education as a basic human right plays a key role when it comes to asserting other fundamental rights.
Investing in early education of Roma children means strengthening the economy of the member countries of the European Union.
According to the MEP, it is necessary to raise awareness of these reports in the widest possible circle, also between Roma and non-Roma.
Indeed, the sooner a Roma child starts school, the greater his chances of becoming a productive member of the labour market; through taxes paid from his income and consumption, he participates in the state budget.
“Because of their European Union nationality, Roma must be assured of their right to quality education, and be protected from low-quality and sectarian education,” said Lívia Járóka.
According to the MEP, the European Union must work together with a goal and action to speed up the process of desegregation of schools, so that compliance with existing and in preparation anti-discrimination directives is of paramount importance.
"We must break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment, and give the opportunities provided by democracy to Roma children, so that they can participate as full citizens in the future of Europe" - demanded Járóka.
In the name of the "European Year for Equal Opportunities" for All, the objective of the Equal Opportunities Summit in Europe held every year since the Berlin Summit last year is to ensure a single platform to support the measures taken to promote equal opportunities and combat discrimination, targeted at European level and at the level of member countries.
