Elites are in danger.
The phenomenon was already manifested a few days ago, with the House vote, contrary to the $700 billion bailout approved by the White House: a significant number of Americans were, and still are, more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the American economy.
And it is the New York Times of yesterday that confirms this by communicating that the current crisis divides the Republican Party, even more divided between its moderate East Coast soul, favorable to the federal institutions as well as the business community, and its new soul, on the contrary, conservative, hostile to "the ones of Washington" and the world of finance, powerful especially in the Central and Southern States.
The soul, precisely, which made itself felt despotically with the vote I was talking about at the beginning.
However, what has just been mentioned is only one example of the changes, the great changes that the current economic earthquake predicts or already lets go: not only in the United States, but throughout the West, and maybe not only here.
In the United States as in Europe, the crisis seems to be accelerating the phenomena that have been brewing for some time, to the point that, in the new climate, they are solidifying and revealing themselves.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the extraordinary stimulus, of the dual state-sovereign category, in relation to a kind of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions that obviously have close relations with abroad, but which, above all, are involved on a large scale, the balance sheets of individuals and families who live in one country, in one state.
This immediately creates a political problem for which it governs: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of individuals and families who are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically, it is almost only here national.
Political internationalisation seems really out of the question or does not have much to say: the obvious evidence is provided by the European Union, which, shared as usual, among the various interests and between the various national strategies, is unable to decide any common political line.
And so it is from the government of each state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and stimulus plans, new rules, and above all a credit affection: when we are going through a difficult period, there are only the states that have the economic resources, the mass of financial resources capable of trying to put things back in place.
They also have the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of inestimable value, elements that no market or international organization can ever have in a similar way.
This new emphasis of the nation-state crisis is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the ever-major importance that the more recent economic developments of the economy tend to attribute to a factor quite linked to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, indeed, while we were convinced that we were now entering the realm of the network, of increasingly sophisticated technology, of the non-material, convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized at once, that our future will instead have to settle its accounts more and more with the rather intangible things like water, harvest.
Things that can certainly be transported from one place to another on earth, but that are absolutely linked to a confined space, to a territory.
So, who is sovereign, certainly has more cards than the one who is not, that is, the one who has the misfortune to live in a place without harvest, without oil and without water.
Now I come to the second novelty, which, however, foresees a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this regard, the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, awareness of the objective need for authoritarian leadership, the search for a person who knows how to take charge of the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leaderships, economic species that have proven inadequate and full of shadows.
And in addition, something even deeper, in a sense, even worrying: discredit, suffering, an image of inadequacy, a sense of distance that tends to involve the entire class of directors in a growing number of Western countries.
Thus the conviction of the various classes increases even more, before the actions are the same ideas of the social elites until now at their peak, their way of listening and being, their culture in the complex acceptance of the term, to have the same time, and to be ever more foreign to the opinions of the majorities.
In short, the demand for leadership, feeds underground, a powerful and branched movement of delegitimizations of either the ruling classes and traditional political orders, which manifest themselves in the improvised electoral "revolts" or else, in the collective mood changes of recent times, from the conservative rise in Austria to Bavaria, to the fall of the Greater Labour Party.
One has the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their format, someone would say, have more and more difficulty, which does not date from today, to understand and therefore to represent the deep layers of Western societies, and that the economic crisis increases and increases and potentially unravels.
In view of all this, talking about a current "rebellion of the masses" on the agenda seems frankly exaggerated.
But we say well, keep your eyes wide open, it is not without reason.
The superglue to walk on the walls.
Defeat the laws of gravity with super glue and, in the future, walk on walls like Spiderman.
This is the goal of various American research centers, and today, a team of four institutes has almost succeeded.
With an adhesive measuring just 2.5 square centimetres, the researchers managed to keep a body of 100 kilograms glued to a vertical wall.
The American journal Science has published the findings of researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material, invented by the team of researchers, is an evolution of those we know who use a particular structure of carbon, called nano carbon tubes.
"The glue principle can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged like a spaghetti pile." explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
Scientists have been inspired by the legs of the geckos, covered with microscopic hairs that ensure the animal is a perfect adherent.
Tests on various materials, such as glass, Teflon, and glass paper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful than the legs of these reptiles, and at the same time, that it “is easily detached from the wall,” says Liming Dai, a research fellow at the University of Dayton’s Faculty of Engineering.
"This material could be used as a temporary adhesive," adds Liming Dai.
Maybe to walk on walls like Spiderman? Maybe so, but researchers think of a much less fascinating use such as the connection between electronic devices, since carbon nanotubes are conductive of heat and electric current.
Other applications may include aerospace engineering.
So far, no superheroes.
