Farewell old Paradiso cinema, cities eliminate historic halls.
Historic cinemas close in favor of Multiplex.
“A city without cinemas is a blind city, it’s like a face without eyes.”
The image provided by the director Giuseppe Tornatore illustrates well what is happening in the major Italian urban centers, but also in the provincial cities,
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth on the periphery of large multi-rooms, and the death of mono-room consumption in the central areas of cities, is one of the major events that seems inevitable and indisputable to us; it also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
Disappearing, they are often historical places and full of memory, "it is as if one of my friends disappears, someone we know, with whom we have shared a path and so many emotions" observes the director of the Nuovo Cine Paradiso, film that offers to Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar as well as the Grand Prix of the Cannes jury, and who always told the film.
The figures provided by Anec, the main trade association, mean everything: in the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and it is the cinemas of the main cities that have paid the most the costs: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, Emilia Romaine leads with 82 mono cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The evidence confirms that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, because it is the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-room cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany as in Emilia-Romagna.
“Italian exploitation has developed irrationally,” observes Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, “it is useful to build new structures, but we should still guarantee the survival of those that already exist, because when a room is closed in a city, these frequenters are not necessarily all willing to go to the multiplexes.
Not to mention the missed deliberation of the credit in favor of traders: the previous debt of the State is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector, it would take between 16 and 18 million euros per year.
Note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about these closures, decided to solve the situation through the signing of a protocol between City Hall and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to defend and promote mono cinemas in historic centers and on the outskirts.
Among the regulations planned, there are measures of tax facilities for managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area, and will have special rates for parking lots and in certain parking lots.
"This is an initiative that I like," observes Giuseppe Tornatore "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna implementing other measures.
It is obvious, however, that to contrast the super power of multiplexes, traditional rooms must also improve the quality of sound and image, as today’s audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Supercinema de Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to do "New Cinema Paradiso" that I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass in front of the Rialto, or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have lived so many shared emotions, I turn to the other side not to see the signs blackened by the dust.
