When the energy is born from the waves, now the big ones are launching.
This is a huge deposit that occupies more than 70% of the planet's surface and now the world's major energy companies are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides, these are the new renewable sources on which colossians like Chevron have laid their eyes, and now they are trying to get their hands on them.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for hundreds of years now, and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research has intensified.
When the price of oil dropped around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now the environmental authorities and the new increase in oil give the sector a big boost.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15% of the world’s electricity needs could be met by sea swell operating systems.
That would be twice the amount produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, there would be currents and tides.
Colossians on the attack.
The first company to focus on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a facility in northern Portugal.
When the deal was announced, it seemed like a real revolutionary step.
Two years after that, more and more candidates among these companies that have always been dedicated to traditional energy are betting on marine energy.
“Chevron is currently studying ocean energy technologies,” a spokesman for a company associated with the U.S. oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, “and it is evaluating opportunities to cooperate with us.”
The cooperation in question involves obtaining a deliberate permit from the US Energy Commission, necessary to give rise to a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
This is a very interesting signal, especially considering that precisely in Alaska, the US continues to extract oil, and recently President Bush has put in place a project for new excavations.
In addition to Chevron, there are Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey, which travel the way of energy from the sea, and the amounts invested to date, although their details are not known, according to observers, a growing interest.
Technology to be developed.
Experts are talking about a technology still in its infancy, aside from the fact that marine energy does not dispel fears about the environmental impact.
At present, systems such as those in Portugal, or some in Scotland, are small in size, and do not seem to create major problems for the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, however, you need to use technologies with a superior environmental impact.
"And the choices are diverse: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys connected to each other.
The thrust of the waves, which causes the mud to move up and down, is converted into a hydraulic pressure of the pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
Pressure turns a turbine, which in turn powers a generator.
The energy is sent to the shore via underwater cables.
For now, we have four such systems in the project phase, pending a single federal approval, and some of the energy could be used for a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces energy for a shopping mall and parking lot using six underwater turbines from New York’s East River.
The movement of the water during the tides, turns the blades of the turbines, creating a rotational movement that feeds a generator.
Verdant has announced that it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to draw energy.
After the waves, the tides.
Particular interest, they say at the Institute for Electrical Energy Research, deserves at the moment, the potential of the tides.
Although this is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable from wind, sun, or waves, and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
And it is precisely on the energy of the tides that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others, look to the coasts, have invested $7.5 million in 2008 and plans to invest up to $35 million in 2009.
